===Etymology===
c. 13th century, {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|broun|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|brun|brūn|lang=ang}} 'dark, shining', from {{proto|Germanic|ƀrūnaz|lang=en}} (compare [[Frisian]] ''brún'', {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|bruin|lang=nl}}, German {{term|braun|lang=de}}), from {{proto|Indo-European|bhreu-|lang=en}} 'shining, brown' (compare {{etyl|lt|-}} {{term|beras|bė́ras|lang=lt}} 'brown', Ancient Greek ''phrýnē, phrŷnos'' 'toad', Sanskrit ''babhrú'' 'reddish-brown' {{rfscript|Devanagari|lang=sa}}).

